category=Getting Started
description=<p>This example shows you how to display a simple message.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Note:</b></font>  Traditionally, the first program written in a new language displays the message &quot;Hello world&quot;.</p>
discussion=<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> message is sent when the user clicks an object. When the <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> message is sent to the field, it triggers this <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> handler.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The first and last lines mark the start and end of the <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> handler. All message handlers begin with the word <font face="Courier" size="11">on</font> and the name of the message (which is also the handler's name), and all handlers end with the word <font face="Courier" size="11">end</font> and the name of the handler.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The handler contains only one statement:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">answer</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &quot;Hello world!&quot;</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>The <font face="Courier" size="11">answer</font> command displays a dialog box with the text you specify. When you click the button, Revolution sends a <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> message to it. The message triggers the <font face="Courier" size="11">mouseUp</font> handler, which displays a dialog box that says &quot;Hello world!&quot;. Click the &quot;Demo&quot; button to try it out.</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><b>Hello World variations:</b></font></p>\n<p>You can display a message in a variety of ways. For example, in the Revolution development environment, you can use the M<font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>essage Box</i></font> to show a message. For more details on the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>Message Box,</i></font> see the section of the same name in the <font face="Lucida Grande" size="11"><i>User's Guide</i></font>. Use the following statement:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &quot;Hello world!&quot;</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>You can also use the <font face="Courier" size="11">put</font> command to put text into any field object:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">put</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &quot;Hello world!&quot; into field &quot;Message&quot;</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p>To display the message automatically when the stack opens, then close the stack when the user dismisses the dialog box, create a stack and put this handler in its script:</p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">on</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> openStack</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">answer</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> &quot;Hello world!&quot;</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">    </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#0000FF">close</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#F88017">me</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier" size="11">  </font><font face="Courier" size="11" color="#980517">end</font><font face="Courier" size="11"> openStack</font></p>
level=2
licensed=false
name=Display Hello World
solution=<p><font color="#980517">on</font> mouseUp</p>\n<p>  <font color="#0000FF">answer</font> &quot;Hello world!&quot;</p>\n<p><font color="#980517">end</font> mouseUp</p>
title=Display "Hello World"